## Why This Is Asked

Evaluates the ability to design privacy-preserving, federated cca_score systems that balance on-device computation with secure aggregation while maintaining robust governance controls.

## Key Concepts

- Federated learning with secure aggregation and differential privacy
- On-device inference ensuring minimal data exposure and consent-based processing
- Idempotency guarantees, drift detection mechanisms, canary rollout strategies, and backpressure management

## Code Example

```javascript
// Example interfaces
type UploadUpdate = {
  user_id_masked: string,
  model_version: string,
  encrypted_payload: string,
  idempotency_key: string,
  consent_token: string,
  timestamp: number
};

type ComputeScore = {
  local_inputs: object,
  model_version: string,
  consent_context: object
};

type DriftDetection = {
  baseline_metrics: object,
  current_metrics: object,
  drift_threshold: number
};
```

## Why This Is Asked
Understanding clock skew handling helps reliable scoring in distributed/mobile contexts.

## Key Concepts
- Clock skew validation, configurable max_skew_ms
- Idempotency keys to prevent duplicate scoring
- Canary toggles for safe rollout and backpressure considerations

## Code Example
```javascript
const now = Date.now();
const skew = Math.abs(now - client_timestamp);
if (skew > max_skew_ms) {
  res.status(400).json({ error: 'SKEW_EXCEEDED' });
  return;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you monitor and adjust max_skew_ms across regions?
- How would you test under mobile device clock drift and network latency?

## Why This Is Asked
Drift detection ensures model reliability and safe fallbacks in production scoring.

## Key Concepts
- Drift detection across model_version switches
- Telemetry fields: drift_flag, drift_reason, score_change_pct, last_model_version, last_score
- Fallback routing and drift alerts
- Observability and basic tests for drift, isolation, and rollback

## Code Example
```javascript
function checkDrift(currentScore, lastScore, lastModelVersion, currentModelVersion, threshold=0.15){
  const drift = Math.abs(currentScore - lastScore);
  const versionChanged = currentModelVersion !== lastModelVersion;
  const driftFlag = drift > threshold || versionChanged;
  const driftReason = versionChanged ? 'model_version_change' : (drift > threshold ? 'score_change' : 'none');
  const scoreChangePct = lastScore ? ((currentScore - lastScore) / Math.abs(lastScore)) * 100 : 0;
  return { driftFlag, driftReason, scoreChangePct };
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you store per-user drift telemetry at scale while preserving privacy?
- How would you tune the threshold and ensure safe fallbacks during rollout?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests system design for real-time collaboration at scale, including choice of transport, state partitioning, conflict resolution, and delivery guarantees.

## Key Concepts

- Real-time collaboration data models (CRDTs vs OT)
- Transport choices (WebSocket vs gRPC)
- Per-room sharding and snapshotting
- Exactly-once vs at-least-once semantics

## Code Example

```javascript
// Simple CRDT merge sketch
class ORSet {
  constructor() { this.add = new Set(); this.remove = new Set(); }
  apply(op) { if (op.type === 'add') this.add.add(op.id); else if (op.type === 'remove') this.remove.add(op.id); }
  value() { return [...this.add].filter(id => !this.remove.has(id)); }
  merge(other) { this.add = new Set([...this.add, ...other.add]); this.remove = new Set([...this.remove, ...other.remove]); }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you horizontally scale 10k rooms with 200 concurrent editors?
- How do you ensure client reconnection replays without duplication?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests the ability to design a reproducible, auditable serverless data pathway under latency constraints, a common real-world constraint in scaling cca_score pipelines.

## Key Concepts
- Idempotent ingestion for batch replays and late arrivals
- Deterministic scoring without randomness to ensure reproducibility
- Content-addressable hashing for inputs and outputs to enable integrity checks
- Immutable storage and a write-ahead ledger for audit trails

## Code Example
```javascript
function computeScoreDeterministic(inputs, modelVersion) {
  const inputHash = sha256(JSON.stringify(inputs));
  const key = modelVersion + ":" + inputHash;
  const score = deterministicModelEval(inputs, modelVersion);
  const scoreHash = sha256(score.toString() + key);
  return { score, scoreHash, inputHash };
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you enforce privacy while preserving auditability?
- How do you handle out-of-order batch arrivals and retries?
- What tests would you add to catch drift across cold starts and deployments?

## Why This Is Asked
Real-world need for a multi-tenant policy engine to enforce per-tenant constraints without downtime.

## Key Concepts
- Policy-as-code and versioning
- Per-tenant gating and feature flags
- Zero-downtime updates, revocation, and rollback
- Observability and auditing for policy changes

## Code Example
```javascript
// Pseudo-policy check
function checkPolicy(tenant, request) {
  const p = policyStore.get(tenant);
  if (!p) return false;
  if (request.model_version !== p.allowedModel) return false;
  if (!p.allowedRegions.includes(request.region)) return false;
  return true;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test policy revocation safety under traffic spikes?
- How would you handle cross-region policy replication and consistency?

