## Why This Is Asked
Tests offline-first design, deterministic scoring, and conflict handling in sync.

## Key Concepts
- Offline-first workflows and local persistence
- Deterministic scoring with seeds for reproducibility
- Conflict resolution strategies (last-write-wins, vector clocks)

## Code Example
```javascript
function scoreBaseline(params, seed){
  let x = seed ^ (params.user_id_masked || '').length;
  x = (x * 1664525) >>> 0;
  const localeFactor = (params.locale || 'en').charCodeAt(0) & 0xff;
  x = (x ^ localeFactor) >>> 0;
  const versionFactor = (params.local_version || 'v1').length;
  x = (x * (versionFactor + 7)) >>> 0;
  const score = Math.abs(x) % 100;
  return score;
}
```

## Why This Is Asked
This question evaluates offline-first architecture design, conflict resolution strategies, and API robustness for clients with unreliable connectivity.

## Key Concepts
- Client-side caching with immediate response
- Version-based conflict resolution using sync tokens
- Idempotent operations for safe retries
- Batch synchronization for network efficiency
- Comprehensive testing under simulated outage conditions

## Code Example
```javascript
// Pseudo-code for offline sync workflow
const cache = new UserScoreCache();
const syncQueue = new OfflineQueue();

function computeCCAScore(userId, data) {
  const score = calculateScore(data);
  const token = cache.update(userId, score);
  syncQueue.enqueue({userId, score, token, timestamp: Date.now()});
  return score;
}

function syncToServer() {
  if (navigator.onLine) {
    const batch = syncQueue.getBatch();
    return fetch('/cca_score/sync', {
      method: 'POST',
      body: JSON.stringify(batch)
    }).then(response => {
      if (response.ok) syncQueue.confirmBatch();
    });
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you handle concurrent client modifications?
- What fallback strategies would you implement for extended outages?
- How would you optimize sync payload size for low-bandwidth connections?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests the ability to design distributed systems that guarantee privacy, fault tolerance, and consistency across geo-distributed edge infrastructure with unreliable connectivity. It evaluates understanding of consensus protocols, state management under partitions, and practical API design.

## Key Concepts
- Hierarchical Byzantine Fault Tolerance (BFT) with regional coordinators
- Append-only global ledger with Merkle tree verification
- Monotonic score progression with sequence numbers and nonces
- Threshold cryptography for privacy preservation
- Partition healing with anti-entropy and state reconciliation
- Cross-region consensus with bounded fault tolerance

## Code Example

```javascript
// Regional share collection and aggregation
class RegionalCoordinator {
  async collectAndSignShares(shares) {
    const signatures = await Promise.all(
      shares.map(share => this.signShare(share))
    );
    const merkleRoot = this.buildMerkleTree(shares);
    const batch = {
      regionId: this.regionId,
      timestamp: Date.now(),
      sequenceNumber: this.nextSequence(),
      merkleRoot,
      thresholdSignature: this.aggregateSignatures(signatures)
    };
    return this.signBatch(batch);
  }
}

// Global aggregator with append-only log
class GlobalAggregator {
  async commitBatch(signedBatch) {
    if (!this.verifySignature(signedBatch)) {
      throw new Error('Invalid batch signature');
    }
    if (!this.isMonotonic(signedBatch.sequenceNumber)) {
      throw new Error('Non-monotonic sequence detected');
    }
    return this.appendToLedger(signedBatch);
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you bound latency and ensure liveness during extended network partitions?
- What formal verification techniques could prove the system's privacy guarantees?
- How would you implement efficient state synchronization when regions reconnect after prolonged partitions?

## Why This Is Asked
This question tests designing a real-time privacy-preserving federation with streaming updates, focusing on DP budgets, monotonic aggregation, replay protection, and fault tolerance.

## Key Concepts
- Real-time streaming aggregation with privacy guarantees
- Per-device DP budgeting and accounting
- Replay protection and clock skew handling
- Throughput considerations and backpressure in edge-to-cloud pipelines

## Code Example
```javascript
// Pseudo-code: validate delta
function processDelta({device_id, ts, delta, nonce, dp_noise}) {
  if (nonce in usedNonces[device_id]) throw 'replay';
  usedNonces[device_id].add(nonce);
  if (ts <= lastTs[device_id]) delta = 0; // monotone
  // apply clipping
  delta = Math.max(-MAX_DELTA, Math.min(MAX_DELTA, delta));
  globalSum += delta + dp_noise;
  budgets[device_id] -= DP_COST;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test privacy budget exhaustion under burst traffic?
- How would you handle device churn and late arrivals without leaking budgets?

